+# Exploration 001: Phase 0 Definition Gate for a Tiny Delayed Trigger
+
+## Goal
+
+Decide whether Tao's tiny delayed trigger can be turned into one preferred exact-NS object that is concrete enough to support a smallest-faithful-support audit, or whether every honest formulation either collapses back to the already-killed five-role singleton circuit or relies on a non-canonical packet backup.
+
+This is a definition-gate exploration. It is not allowed to drift into a broad Tao survey or a full coefficient campaign. Its job is to define the exact object, or explain precisely why no such object survives.
+
+## Decision Target
+
+State one decision target first and organize the report around it:
+
+```text
+Either there exists one preferred exact tiny-trigger object, with explicit smallness,
+delay, visibility, leakage, and back-reaction bookkeeping, that is sharp enough for
+Phase 1 support auditing, or every honest trigger definition either reduces to the
+previous five-role exact object or requires a non-canonical packet backup, so the
+strategy should stop early.
+```
+
+## Preloaded Context
